  "prompt": "Why do converts to Islam say that they have reverted to Islam?",
  "response": "Converts to Islam often use the term \"revert\" instead of \"convert\" because they believe that Islam is the natural or original state of human beings. This belief is based on the Islamic concept of \"fitrah,\" which suggests that every person is born with an innate disposition towards monotheism and the worship of one God. \n\nAccording to this view, when someone embraces Islam, they are not converting to a new religion but rather returning to their natural state of belief in one God. This is why they might say they have \"reverted\" to Islam, indicating a return to their original, inherent faith. \n\nThis perspective is supported by a hadith (a saying of the Prophet Muhammad) in which he states, \"Every child is born on the fitrah. Then his parents make him a Jew, a Christian, or a Magian.\" This hadith underscores the idea that Islam considers itself the default religion of humanity, and conversion to Islam is seen as a reversion to this natural state.",
